getting the platform there. So I'm really looking forward for that.

00:04:41.519 --> 00:04:46.679
That's great. So to be able to put us all in kind of your team's mindset, would you be able

00:04:46.679 --> 00:04:50.359
to give us an example of some of the work that your team's doing?

00:04:51.160 --> 00:04:57.399
Sure. So when I said I'm in delivery, global delivery, lead pricing analytics means like

00:04:57.399 --> 00:05:03.079
platform means a lot for different organizations, let me put it in, you know, in a easier box.

00:05:03.079 --> 00:05:10.040
So the platform lead comes with responsibilities in terms of security, because AXA Excel being,

00:05:10.040 --> 00:05:16.760
you know, one of the global players, and also insurance and commercial space. It's very much

00:05:16.760 --> 00:05:22.040
data privacy, GDPR, and all the other security regulatory is quite hard for us. We have to be

00:05:22.040 --> 00:05:26.760
very, very careful with the data we handle, and also with all the integrations of different

00:05:26.920 --> 00:05:33.720
systems. So my role is to ensure that I'm aligning to all the security policies that is put forward

00:05:33.720 --> 00:05:40.600
by information security, as well as it also comes with operational work, like all the data analytics

00:05:40.600 --> 00:05:45.640
work and all the data science work, pricing work, because we use RStudio also for pricing.

00:05:46.760 --> 00:05:51.320
Because in insurance, if you see, we have pricing as one of the important functionality of

00:05:51.320 --> 00:05:56.440
underwriting. So we use it for that as well. So we have to ensure that the platform is stable.

00:05:57.399 --> 00:06:02.600
And there is one property model we have for pricing, which I can say that 24 by seven,

00:06:02.600 --> 00:06:09.239
it should be up running. So that is, again, it comes under my responsibility. And apart from that,

00:06:09.239 --> 00:06:14.519
you know, definitely the budgets, right? So anything you run in terms of platform, it's not

00:06:14.519 --> 00:06:19.720
that you have huge investment to do, but you have to make sure that you have the right platform

00:06:19.720 --> 00:06:26.200
to have huge investment to do. So with the budgets, like given budgets, and also considering

00:06:26.200 --> 00:06:31.720
what is coming in terms of expansion from different users, I have to ensure that everything goes by

00:06:31.720 --> 00:06:37.480
line. So that's quite, you know, in a summary. And along with that, it comes all the other

00:06:37.480 --> 00:06:44.600
responsibilities that's tied to it. Thank you. That's really helpful. I see Alice just started

00:06:44.600 --> 00:06:49.720
off with some questions in the chat. And Alice mentioned she can't unmute right now. So I'm going

00:06:49.720 --> 00:06:55.079
to read the question for her. But it's, hi, I'm curious, what were the key factors that led you

00:06:55.079 --> 00:06:59.880
to want to migrate to the cloud? And how many data folks do you have in the organization?

00:07:01.079 --> 00:07:07.239
Okay, so the main reason why we are moving to cloud is not only for this particular platform.

00:07:08.200 --> 00:07:15.480
It's the whole decision of the corporate taken by AXA and then AXA Excel. By 2023, we wanted

00:07:15.480 --> 00:07:21.959
all the data centers to be gone. And we went with private cloud. And now it's more of hybrid,

00:07:21.959 --> 00:07:27.799
choosing private and public. It's the decision of moving to cloud is again, you know, different

00:07:27.799 --> 00:07:33.720
reasons. One is the operational cost, definitely. Because if you see, we had, so when I say AXA

00:07:33.720 --> 00:07:41.000
Excel, we are part of Excel group and Excel group acquired Katlin. Then we were again, you know,

00:07:41.559 --> 00:07:47.320
acquired by AXA. So we have like, say, three integrations gone into this whole of this

00:07:47.320 --> 00:07:52.679
acquisition. And because of that, the technology stack is huge. And we are trying to streamline

00:07:52.679 --> 00:07:58.359
everything. And in terms of the cost also, we wanted to say that, okay, move it to cloud. And

00:07:58.920 --> 00:08:04.440
cloud is also, you know, way of looking into saying by demand, you put on the infrastructure

00:08:04.440 --> 00:08:11.160
rather than just giving the maximum. So that is the thought process behind. But I will also, yes,

00:08:11.160 --> 00:08:17.559
agree to a point that cloud could be pricey. It could come up with its own, you know, different

00:08:17.559 --> 00:08:25.000
way of configuring it. And but since we know how much we have spent all these years in terms of

00:08:25.079 --> 00:08:30.679
on-prem, we have something like on comparative basis. And we'll try to be within that.

00:08:31.880 --> 00:08:36.840
But I can't promise saying that definitely it's going to be cheaper than the on-prem.

00:08:40.919 --> 00:08:49.960
Thank you. I had a question as well. I know we get to talk about this a little bit. And we talked

00:08:49.960 --> 00:08:56.359
a few weeks ago about it, but I know you did a lot around the governance and security of the

00:08:56.359 --> 00:09:02.200
platform. And I would love to just hear what your experience has been like going through that

00:09:02.200 --> 00:09:06.440
process, because I know there's a lot of people who might be listening in who are just starting

00:09:06.440 --> 00:09:12.599
off with that in their own organizations. Sure. So, you know, it's quite, you know,

00:09:12.599 --> 00:09:16.280
I'm going to be talking about this, I think, throughout my career, because this is something

00:09:16.280 --> 00:09:22.760
which I have really enjoyed doing it. So the platform, when I started managing it two years

00:09:22.760 --> 00:09:31.559
back, it was, you know, all managed by the business users. So there was a bit of, you know,

00:09:31.559 --> 00:09:37.320
hidden detail, I can say, like a black box. We don't know what was the models that were sitting

00:09:37.320 --> 00:09:42.440
there. Also, we don't know who were the users, because it was being expanded to different

00:09:42.440 --> 00:09:48.200
departments within the organization. It started like a POC. And I think it started expanding to

00:09:48.200 --> 00:09:53.799
different business units, because they saw the benefits that was coming out of it. And then it

00:09:53.799 --> 00:10:00.440
was also picked up by one of the biggest property model pricing. So it had its own, you know,

00:10:00.440 --> 00:10:06.039
visibility in terms of, oh, we can do some in this platform, all these things. And from always

00:10:06.039 --> 00:10:10.760
from the for the users who have been on Excel sheet for some time, you're giving a platform

00:10:10.760 --> 00:10:16.520
which comes with its own benefits, they will love to use it. So that's how it started onboarding.

00:10:16.520 --> 00:10:22.119
There was very, very thin line of support already there. When I say support, that was in terms of

00:10:22.119 --> 00:10:28.200
making sure the service doesn't go down, and also onboarding the new users. So that was the minimal

00:10:28.200 --> 00:10:36.359
thing I saw when I entered this unit. And then I have to take the maturity as my priority, because

00:10:36.359 --> 00:10:41.960
as I said earlier, the operational cost is something, you know, as a delivery leader, I have

00:10:41.960 --> 00:10:48.280
to make sure that we are within that, and also security, because tech debt and security became

00:10:48.280 --> 00:10:54.760
priority after AXA acquisition for us. So with all this as my main objectives, I said without

00:10:54.760 --> 00:10:59.960
even knowing what is there inside the black box, it will be very difficult. So we started with the

00:10:59.960 --> 00:11:06.440
journey of the maturity of what I was talking about. It was due diligence that first I wanted

00:11:06.440 --> 00:11:12.679
to do in terms of understanding what has gone in the system, and also how to bring the stabilization

00:11:12.679 --> 00:11:18.039
of the platform, because we also had complaints that it was mainly for the property pricing,

00:11:18.919 --> 00:11:23.960
the platform was coming down, and they were not knowing the reason what was happening.

00:11:24.599 --> 00:11:29.719
Is it with the service? Is it with the network? Is it with the application? So that's where I think

00:11:29.719 --> 00:11:35.000
our studio team also really helped us, and Kevin Hayden is here. So he was so helpful.

00:11:36.520 --> 00:11:41.719
He got the engineers, and we did a complete architecture review. So due diligence was going

00:11:41.719 --> 00:11:46.919
on one side, the inventory. I will also tell how I did the inventory, because that might be useful

00:11:46.919 --> 00:11:53.239
for many of them here. So it's a huge organization, different departments. I don't know anyone in

00:11:53.239 --> 00:11:59.320
person as well. So what we did was, and they're all spread across the global region. So what we

00:11:59.320 --> 00:12:04.599
said was, okay, let's start doing a questionnaire. So it was a simple questionnaire prepared with,

00:12:04.599 --> 00:12:09.479
you know, a lot more questions for us to first understand who are you, what are you doing here,

00:12:09.479 --> 00:12:14.919
and what is your pipeline, and how many, you know, models you have, what is your data sources,

00:12:14.919 --> 00:12:20.359
and that was the type of the questions. And we sent it out. We collected all the information,

00:12:20.359 --> 00:12:25.400
which was very, very helpful for us to say that, okay, this is what the platform is getting used

00:12:25.400 --> 00:12:31.640
for. And then one by one, we need to come out with the plan of, we call that as application

00:12:31.640 --> 00:12:38.679
currency, because, you know, we also quantify that whatever changes you bring into the platform.

00:12:38.679 --> 00:12:44.679
So we started with those projects to get to the maturity level. And there were quite a lot that

00:12:44.679 --> 00:12:50.440
has been done over the two years, and still I'm saying that we are still in progress. I won't say

00:12:50.440 --> 00:12:56.119
it's closed, because, you know, for a platform like this, where we have a number of users,

00:12:56.119 --> 00:13:02.679
we can talk about IDE users, we have around 200 to 250 users. And in terms of Connect viewers,

00:13:02.679 --> 00:13:09.479
we have around 1,250. So for such a platform, you know, it never goes. There is still work,

00:13:09.479 --> 00:13:17.640
we are, it's going. Did you learn a lot more about the team through that survey? I think

00:13:17.640 --> 00:13:23.880
that's a great idea of surveying the users to see how they're actually using it. Yes, definitely,

00:13:23.880 --> 00:13:28.119
because I want to hear both, you know, the positive and the negative side, like what were

00:13:28.119 --> 00:13:33.320
they getting from technology, because I belong to technology. So I want to understand. One thing I'm

00:13:33.320 --> 00:13:38.359
very much, you know, I can say that that's something I keep it as, you know, one of my

00:13:38.359 --> 00:13:44.520
main objectives. Also, business users are doing something in a platform means that they are

00:13:44.520 --> 00:13:50.440
already, you know, creating some business value. It's all coming back. So I'm keen to help the

00:13:50.440 --> 00:13:55.400
business community. But at the same time, being from technology, I need to ensure, you know,

00:13:55.400 --> 00:14:02.200
the technology guidelines are also followed. So I think that particular survey helped us to think

00:14:02.200 --> 00:14:06.760
what are the challenges they are seeing from technology, and also to understand, you know,

00:14:06.760 --> 00:14:13.239
what they want us to do going forward in terms of their pipeline. And also certain things like how

00:14:13.239 --> 00:14:19.320
are they connecting to data sources, and you know, so it was both. It's a very, very insightful,

00:14:19.320 --> 00:14:27.159
I think, answers which we got. I'm so excited to have you here today to be able to provide that

00:14:27.159 --> 00:14:32.919
like IT and technology background and your perspective, because I know a lot of times

00:14:33.559 --> 00:14:38.760
there's questions on here about working with IT for the first time. And as a data scientist,

00:14:38.760 --> 00:14:44.200
how do you like build relationships with IT? And I see somebody asked anonymously,

00:14:44.200 --> 00:14:50.119
what's the relationship between data scientists and IT or platform team like at your company?

00:14:51.400 --> 00:14:58.440
I will say very, very collaborative. See, one thing I believe in is technology cannot

00:14:58.440 --> 00:15:03.239
achieve what they want to achieve without the business. And it's the same for business users

00:15:03.239 --> 00:15:08.599
also, the data scientists, they can't do what they want without the technology, because some of these

00:15:08.599 --> 00:15:13.159
requests which is coming from them. Simple example, I'll give you in terms of the packages

00:15:13.159 --> 00:15:18.039
they need, for example, right? Sometimes when it comes to us, we need to understand the importance

00:15:18.039 --> 00:15:23.000
of it and quickly turn it around. And at the same time, their deployment. So now recently,

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:28.119
we implemented proper deployment release management for all our models. So nothing goes

00:15:28.119 --> 00:15:32.919
to production without going through the deployment, which we call it as release management.

00:15:32.919 --> 00:15:38.760
And there, you know, I can understand being 20 years in technology. For other applications,

00:15:38.760 --> 00:15:44.599
it's okay, we get that particular build after, say, three days or four days, or even a month

00:15:44.599 --> 00:15:49.719
planning can be done. But for analytics, they want something to the market very quickly. They

00:15:49.719 --> 00:15:54.280
wanted to give the scoring models to underwriters. They wanted to give the pricing models very

00:15:54.280 --> 00:16:01.000
quickly in terms of, you know, change in inflation and things like that. So what we did was I have

00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:07.000
to come up with a different plan of release management, saying that, okay, let's put,

00:16:07.000 --> 00:16:12.280
you know, let's customize it. We won't treat every model as an application and go through

00:16:12.280 --> 00:16:19.080
the entire change management. We will go through a very, very thin line, only the minimal, right?

00:16:19.080 --> 00:16:23.640
The basics, what we need to do in terms of the guidelines. So we have to customize everything

00:16:23.640 --> 00:16:29.880
for our data scientists. And I think they saw that when first, when I talked about bringing

00:16:29.960 --> 00:16:33.799
in guardrails and, you know, all that, they were thinking, oh, this is going to be

00:16:34.359 --> 00:16:39.239
complicating what we do now. We are not going to have the flexibility and we are not going to have

00:16:39.239 --> 00:16:44.840
that efficiency, which we had earlier. But now they are seeing why did I do it and how come it

00:16:44.840 --> 00:16:50.679
has streamlined their process. And now it's, you know, it's become like more easy for me to go and

00:16:50.679 --> 00:16:56.679
tell them this is what I'm planning to do for the next phase. So I took time, but I think now it's

00:16:56.679 --> 00:17:00.280
been two years and without their help, I will not be able to do anything.

00:17:03.159 --> 00:17:08.599
It's a really, really helpful perspective to hear. Do you have any, any tips for,

00:17:08.599 --> 00:17:13.079
for everybody listening in if they're just getting started working with the IT team?

00:17:13.800 --> 00:17:21.479
Yes. So, you know, the tips is really for the IT team to understand the value of what you're doing,

00:17:22.199 --> 00:17:27.000
because everything you do, like data scientists, there is something going to be an output. It

00:17:27.000 --> 00:17:30.680
could take one week, it could take a month, or even it could take six months, which you are

00:17:30.680 --> 00:17:36.040
doing an R&D. But for them to understand the value we're going to bring in is going to be very,

00:17:36.040 --> 00:17:41.959
very important. And also explaining to them the flexibility you need, because analytics and,

00:17:41.959 --> 00:17:47.079
you know, the data science is all about the speed that comes with any platform. It could be any

00:17:47.079 --> 00:17:51.560
platform, right? So that is something which you need to explain to them. I'm fine. I'm here to

00:17:51.560 --> 00:17:56.520
support in terms of the governance or security or stability, what you want to bring in, even

00:17:56.520 --> 00:18:01.959
the operational cost. But at the same time, can I get this? So it's always, you know, two ways.

00:18:01.959 --> 00:18:07.479
So if you say, I'm going to be really supportive of your quadrails, but at the same time, I'm

00:18:07.479 --> 00:18:13.319
expecting this from your team, I think it's going to be more good. And definitely I feel that that

00:18:13.319 --> 00:18:17.800
collaboration is required. Like I said, otherwise, it's very, very difficult to

00:18:17.800 --> 00:18:25.000
make this platform mature. And one thing what I'm seeing now is after this journey, two years

00:18:25.000 --> 00:18:31.239
journey, the platform has matured. And now we both know how we work. I mean, each team knows how we

00:18:31.239 --> 00:18:38.359
work. And there are sometimes trade-offs, both sides, but we are able to take up that. The reason

00:18:38.359 --> 00:18:44.280
being, finally, we wanted to give the best to the output for our business and for the business to

00:18:44.280 --> 00:18:49.719
earn the profits what they want. So finally, the objective is same, both for technology and the

00:18:49.719 --> 00:18:56.520
data scientist world. But I think where that sort of conflict comes in is, you know, when objectives,

00:18:56.520 --> 00:19:02.439
there is no shared vision. So to get that shared vision, I think both teams need to talk.

00:19:03.000 --> 00:19:04.920
That's very important.

00:19:07.160 --> 00:19:12.839
Absolutely. I see there's an anonymous question that came in, and I think it'd be helpful to

00:19:12.839 --> 00:19:19.640
clarify for people here. They said, how did the decision of using RStudio as the cloud service

00:19:19.640 --> 00:19:26.839
provider come to fruition? How did you overcome the question of why not AWS or Azure or Google

00:19:26.839 --> 00:19:29.640
kind of questions? So could you clarify a little bit about the cloud?

00:19:29.719 --> 00:19:36.280
Yeah, definitely. So I think it's, I mean, I won't take the entire credit. Like I said,

00:19:36.280 --> 00:19:42.040
it's the users, it's the business users. I think I mentioned this to Kevin sometime back.

00:19:42.040 --> 00:19:48.119
They saw the flexibility that comes with RStudio. When I say flexibility, it's not like just,

00:19:48.119 --> 00:19:53.560
you know, without any guardrails going and using it. They know that entire governance is there,

00:19:53.560 --> 00:19:59.000
but what they saw it is like the IDE. Now, after the workbench, we have the launcher,

00:19:59.000 --> 00:20:03.160
so which they felt that it's one of the good functionality that came out because, you know,

00:20:03.160 --> 00:20:08.040
you have Python, Jupyter Notebook, anything they can launch and also package management.

